The experience variable has a max of 43 and appears continuous rather than catagorical, we may want to consider dropping these negative observations. Education has 3 levels and is a catagorical variable in this dataset.

Classification Models

Data Preparation

Earlier we noticed that education appears to be a catagorical variable in this dataset, here we will create a model matrix with dummies for the levels of education.

dta.temp = loans
dta.temp$Education = factor(dta.temp$Education)   
feats.temp = model.matrix(Personal.Loan~.,data=dta.temp)[,-1]
resp.temp = loans$Personal.Loan

one_hot = data.frame(feats.temp, 'Personal.Loan'=resp.temp);

temp.loans = one_hot
temp.loans$Personal.Loan = ifelse(temp.loans$Personal.Loan==1, 'Accepted', 'Not_Accepted');

Here we use min max scaling to normalize the dataset, later we will want to have this on hand.

maxs <- apply(one_hot[,], 2, max)
mins <- apply(one_hot[,], 2, min);

  scaled.data <- as.data.frame(scale(one_hot[,],center = mins, scale = maxs - mins));

Logistic Regression

set.seed(1)

  glm.fit = glm(factor(Personal.Loan)~., data=temp.loans[train,], family='binomial') # Fitting on the training set

  glm.probs = predict(glm.fit, temp.loans[test,], type='response') # Predicting on the test set
  
  contrasts(factor(temp.loans$Personal.Loan));

ROC: Logistic Regression

pred = prediction(glm.probs, factor(temp.loans[test,12]))
perf = performance(pred,"tpr", "fpr")
{plot(perf, colorize= T, lwd=3)
abline(a=0,b=1, col='grey', lty=2)};

  auc_ROCR = performance(pred, "auc")
  auc_ROCR.glm = auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
  auc_ROCR.glm;
## [1] 0.9583469
  cuts = performance(pred,'acc') # returns an object full of performance metrics
  cutoffs = cuts@x.values[[1]]
  accuracy = cuts@y.values[[1]];

  cutoffs[904];
##      3569 
## 0.6280955

Confusion Matrix: Logistic Regression

We are able to achieve a high auc of .958 but from the confusion matrix we can see that we classified quite a few observations who accepted their loan offer as ‘not accepted’, these are known as false negatives. Since the goal is to increase the number of accepted loans and making an offer has little cost associated for the bank we would rather have a few more false positives than false negatives. We don’t want to send offers to people who have a very low probability of accepting. If we can increase the recall without losing too much precision the bank may be able to save a significant amount of money.

pred.glm = ifelse(glm.probs > 0.6280955, 'Not_Accepted','Accepted') #assign labels based on the threshold that maximizes accuracy

  table(pred.glm, temp.loans[test,12]) # Confusion Matrix
##               
## pred.glm       Accepted Not_Accepted
##   Accepted           78           19
##   Not_Accepted       29          874
  glm.acc = 1-mean(pred.glm!=temp.loans[test,12]); #  Accuracy = true pos + true neg / (true pos + true neg + false pos + false neg)
  glm.rec = 78/(78+29) #recall = TP/ TP + FN
  glm.pcn = 78/(78+19) #precision = TP / TP + FP
  
  glm.table = data.frame('Model'='Logistic Regression','Accuracy'= glm.acc, 'Recall'=glm.rec, 'Precision'= glm.pcn, 'AUC' = auc_ROCR.glm)
  glm.table
##                 Model Accuracy   Recall Precision       AUC
## 1 Logistic Regression    0.952 0.728972 0.8041237 0.9583469

Random Forest

Grid Search: Random Forest

Instead of setting mtry=sqrt(p) we will use a grid search to determine the optimal value. It looks like setting mtry=5 produces the best auc result.

set.seed(1)

control = trainControl(method="cv", 
                       number=10, 
                       repeats = 3, 
                       search="grid",
                       classProbs = TRUE,
                       summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)
## Warning: `repeats` has no meaning for this resampling method.
tunegrid = expand.grid(.mtry=c(1:11))
rf_gridsearch = caret::train(factor(Personal.Loan)~., 
                       data=temp.loans[train,], 
                       method="rf", 
                       metric="ROC", 
                       tuneGrid=tunegrid, 
                       trControl=control,
                       ntree=50);

Fitting the Final Model: Random Forest

After trying some different values for the number of trees to grow it appears that setting ntrees=~30 will yield the best results.

set.seed(1)
control = trainControl(method="none", classProbs = T, summaryFunction = twoClassSummary)
tunegrid = expand.grid(.mtry=5)
rf_final = caret::train(factor(Personal.Loan)~., 
                       data=temp.loans[train,], 
                       method="rf", 
                       metric="ROC", 
                       tuneGrid=tunegrid, 
                       trControl=control,
                       importance=TRUE,
                       ntree=30);

Grid Search: Boosting

We start with a random set of parameters and find the best parameters. After that we “zoom in” around the best parameter to see if we can improve the performance even more. By performing our grid search in steps we can reduce computation time dramatically.

set.seed(1)
xgb.grid = expand.grid( nrounds = c(6500,7500),
                        max_depth = 5,
                        eta = .001,
                        gamma = 0,
                        min_child_weight = 1,
                        colsample_bytree = 1,
                        subsample = c(.8,1));
                      

fitControl = trainControl(method='cv', number= 10, classProbs = T,  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary);

xgb.cv = caret::train(x = x.train, 
                       y= factor(y.train),
                       method='xgbTree',
                       metric='ROC',
                       trControl= fitControl,
                       tuneGrid= xgb.grid);

K-Nearest Neighbors

We use the normalized data with min max scaling to improve performance, since KNN is calculating the distance between observations we want everything on the same scale.

scaled.data$Personal.Loan = ifelse(scaled.data$Personal.Loan==1, 'Accepted', 'Not_Accepted');

Choosing K

Fitting the Best Model: NN

The best model used 10 hidden nodes in the first layer, 10 in the second, and 1 in the last. We skip using the caret package to make plotting the network a bit easier

set.seed(1)

train.numeric =ifelse(scale.train.y=='Accepted', 1, 0)
test.numeric =ifelse(scale.test.y=='Accepted', 1, 0)

mlp.fit = mlp(x=scale.train.x, y=train.numeric, size=c(10,10,1), linOut = F)

plot.nnet(mlp.fit)

nn.probs = predict(mlp.fit, scale.test.x, type='prob');

ROC: NN

pred = prediction(nn.probs, test.numeric)

Confusion Matrix: NN

Here we can see that the neural network is able to give us a model with an extremely low false positive rate, if we were to use this model we could be confident that people who are predicted to accept the loan offer will actually accept. Compared to the boosted model we have a few more false negatives, if our goal is to maximize the total number of loans accepted we could use another model or just send offers to everyone but the neural network and boosted model provide a good balance of both precision and recall.
